Source: Gold Mining at Waihi (Glossary)
Author: McARA
Vol / Page: 326
Edition:
Quote: `Lay` of wire rope: Most of the winding-ropes were what was known as `lang lay', in which the strand wires were twisted in the same direction as the strands. They presented a larger surface to resist wear when made in this way and the rope was more easily inspected for internal wear.
